data.name: AMPK
data.value: The AMPK enzyme is the master metabolic switch in each of your cells. When AMPK levels increase you get an energy boost, blood glucose is regulated, insulin sensitivity improves, reduced triglycerides, and increased fat-burning in mitochondria. The metabolism of the whole organism becomes considerably more efficient

data.name: Antioxidant
data.value: A substance that is able to protect the body from oxidaitve stress (from free radicals) either by neutralising the radical or by protecting tissues, or both.

data.name: BloodBrainBarrier
data.value: The blood–brain barrier protects against circulating toxins or pathogens that could cause brain infections, while at the same time allowing vital nutrients to reach the brain.

data.name: Cortisol
data.value: The major stress hormone of the body. In excess, cortisol can result int he breakdown of tissues, resulting in degenerative disease.

data.name: CReactiveProtein
data.value: CRP is a protein secreted mostly by cells in the liver in response to a variety of inflammatory cytokines. CRP plays important roles in inflammatory processes including by altering pathways involved in apoptosis, phagocytosis, nitric oxide release and production of cytokines. Elevated CRP is a reliable marker of chronic inflammation.

data.name: FreeRadicals
data.value: Free radicals result from oxidation in cells and damage tissues in the body. They are implicated in many types of age-related diseases.

data.name: HumanGrowthHormone
data.value: Peptide hormone that stimulates growth, cell reproduction, and cell regeneration in humans and other animals. It is thus important in human development. GH also stimulates production of IGF-1 and increases the concentration of glucose and free fatty acids.

data.name: Mitochondria
data.value: The organelles of cells responsible for producing all of our ATP (cellular energy)

data.name: Mitochondrial
data.value: Relating to the 'mitochondria':the organelles of cells responsible for producing all of our ATP (cellular energy)

data.name: Mitochondriogenesis
data.value: Stimulates the growth of new mitochondria and the repair of existing ones.

data.name: NAD
data.value: NAD+ mediates the production of the energy our cells need to function and survive, fueling enzymes key in repairing DNA damage. As we age, this indispensable molecule progressively declines.

data.name: Neuromelanins
data.value: Pigments that form in the brain that are similar to the melanin pigment in the skin.

data.name: Nootropic
data.value: Nootropics can help to improve memory, boost learning ability, enhance mood and assist overall brain function and health.

data.name: OxidativeStress
data.value: Damage to tissues and cells caused by free radicals, which is implicated in many chronic, degenerative diseases.

data.name: BDNF
data.value: A potent neurotrophin that stimulates the genesis of new neurons in the brain is referred to as neurogenesis. BDNF is implicated in neuroplasticity, learning, memory and higher thinking.

data.name: Neuroplasticity
data.value: Neuroplasticity or brain plasticity is the inherent ability of the brain to adapt and change in reaction to internal and external stimuli. Your brain can change its functions and even its physical structure to react to inputs coming in from events, experiences, thoughts, and even human emotions.
